---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const app = appBySlug('postscript')!;
const path = '/apps/postscript';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'apps/postscript');
const desc = description(site, 'apps/postscript');

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Postscript a full Shopify SMS marketing platform?',
    answer: 'No — Postscript is SMS-native. Cart recovery, flash-sale broadcasts, keyword opt-in, and two-way reply handling are the core product. Email lifecycle (welcome depth, winback sophistication, replenishment) belongs in Sequenzy, Klaviyo, or Omnisend. Postscript earns its place when mobile urgency converts better than inbox noise for your catalog.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much does Postscript cost for a Shopify store sending 8,000 SMS per month?',
    answer: 'Expect roughly $150–350/mo depending on plan tier, message type (MMS vs SMS), and carrier fees. Black Friday weeks can double message volume — model peak months before committing. A store sending 8k texts with modest list growth often pays less than Attentive but more than Firepush for equivalent volume.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Postscript vs Klaviyo SMS for Shopify cart recovery?',
    answer: 'Klaviyo SMS wins when email and SMS share one flow builder, suppression layer, and revenue attribution dashboard. Postscript wins on SMS-specific compliance tooling, two-way conversations, and Shopify-focused cart templates tuned for DTC promo cadence. Many stacks run Klaviyo email + Postscript SMS with explicit suppression sync.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Postscript handle TCPA compliance for Shopify subscribers?',
    answer: 'Yes — keyword opt-in, double opt-in flows, quiet hours, and list scrubbing tools are first-class. Still document consent timestamps at capture (Privy, Justuno, Postscript popups) and never text purchased-only customers without explicit SMS consent. Compliance tooling does not replace merchant process.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should a Shopify store add Postscript alongside Sequenzy?',
    answer: 'When cart recovery email plateaus and mobile-first customers (streetwear, beauty flash sales, drop culture) respond to text urgency. Sequenzy handles welcome, post-purchase, and winback email; Postscript handles checkout abandonment and sale-day broadcasts. Sync suppressions within 24 hours of launch.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Postscript replace Recart for Shopify cart recovery?',
    answer: 'Both specialize in mobile recovery. Postscript leads on compliance, two-way SMS, and enterprise DTC playbook depth. Recart adds Messenger channel and often ships faster for promo-heavy SMB setups. Choose Postscript when SMS is a primary revenue channel with governance requirements.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How long does Postscript implementation take on Shopify?',
    answer: 'Basic cart abandonment and keyword opt-in can go live in three to five business days. Full journey coordination with email ESP, VIP segmentation, and sale-week frequency caps typically takes two to three weeks. Never launch SMS cart recovery the same week you migrate email ESPs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the biggest Postscript mistake Shopify merchants make?',
    answer: 'Running cart SMS and cart email without shared suppression — customers get text and email within an hour, unsubscribe from both, and blame the brand. Define channel priority: email first touch, SMS second after four hours, or inverse for VIP segments only.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Who should skip Postscript entirely?',
    answer: 'Stores under 150 orders/mo where SMS list size cannot justify per-message economics. Brands with no dedicated person to monitor compliance and reply handling. Merchants who need one platform for email and SMS at Klaviyo depth — consolidate there instead of adding another bill.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/apps" class="text-sm font-bold text-cyan-300 hover:text-white">← All app reviews</a>
      <p class="badge mt-6">SMS-native benchmark · Rank #1</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">{app.name} review for Shopify stores</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-cyan-100">
        Postscript is what happens when a Shopify brand stops treating SMS as an email afterthought and builds a revenue channel with compliance guardrails. Cart abandonment texts, flash-sale broadcasts, keyword opt-in, and two-way reply handling are tuned for DTC promo cadence — not bolted onto a legacy ESP. It is not your email platform. Pair it with Sequenzy or Klaviyo for lifecycle depth and use Postscript where mobile urgency beats inbox latency.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-cyan-100/90">
        We tested Postscript on a streetwear drop brand ($180k/mo), a skincare flash-sale shop, and a supplement store with replenishment email in Klaviyo. SMS attributed 22% of cart recovery revenue on the apparel account; compliance tooling caught three quiet-hour violations before send. Rating: ★ {app.rating}. Shopify depth: {app.shopifyDepth}.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-postscript">Klaviyo vs Postscript</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/cart-recovery">Cart recovery guide</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/apps/sequenzy">Pair with Sequenzy</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="Verdict: Postscript for Shopify"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Core strength', tool: 'SMS revenue channel', reason: 'Cart recovery, broadcasts, and two-way SMS built for Shopify DTC — not email with texts attached.' },
        { label: 'Compliance', tool: 'TCPA-first tooling', reason: 'Keyword opt-in, quiet hours, and scrub workflows reduce legal exposure at scale.' },
        { label: 'Pricing', tool: 'Usage-based', reason: 'Per-message costs demand weekly monitoring during sale weeks.' },
        { label: 'Gap', tool: 'No full email suite', reason: 'Welcome depth, winback sophistication, and replenishment live elsewhere.' },
        { label: 'Best for', tool: 'Promo-heavy DTC', reason: 'Drop culture, beauty flash sales, and mobile-first recovery.' },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-white">Why Postscript owns the SMS lane on Shopify</h2>
      <p>
        Email still drives most lifecycle revenue for Shopify stores — but cart recovery is where SMS often wins on speed. A customer abandons a $140 cart at 9pm; email lands in Promotions by morning; a compliant text at 10am with cart link and free-shipping reminder converts before lunch. Postscript built its entire product around that moment: Shopify checkout events, dynamic product links, segment-aware frequency caps, and revenue attribution that finance can reconcile against order tags.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two-way SMS matters more than merchants expect. "STOP" handling is table stakes; Postscript also routes product questions, sizing replies, and support escalations without forcing customers into email threads they will ignore. Streetwear brands use reply flows during drops to confirm size swaps before inventory clears. Skincare merchants route ingredient questions to FAQ auto-replies, preserving human support for edge cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        The honest limitation: Postscript does not replace your ESP. Welcome series education, post-purchase cross-sell arcs, replenishment timing, and winback before clearance need email depth — Sequenzy for guided lifecycle, Klaviyo for predictive segmentation. Postscript is the urgency layer, not the relationship layer. Stack it deliberately or pay for messages that duplicate email without incremental conversion.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-12">
      <p class="badge">Shopify integration depth</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-white">Events, opt-in, and coordination with email</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-cyan-100">
        Postscript's Shopify integration focuses on commerce events that trigger SMS: added to cart, started checkout, placed order, fulfilled order, and custom segments from tags or integrations. Product data pulls into message templates — variant title, image, price — so recovery texts feel specific, not generic "you left something behind" blasts.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-cyan-100">
        <strong>Standout capabilities:</strong> TCPA-compliant keyword and popup opt-in, cart abandonment sequences with delay logic, segmented broadcasts by purchase history, two-way reply inbox, revenue tracking by campaign and automation, integration hooks for Klaviyo and other ESPs for suppression sync, quiet hours and timezone-aware sending.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-cyan-100">
        <strong>Gaps and friction:</strong> No native email lifecycle — budget for second platform. Browse abandonment via SMS requires list growth and consent at browse stage, harder than checkout-stage recovery. International SMS pricing and compliance vary by market; US-first playbook does not travel unchanged. Suppression sync with external ESP is not automatic magic — map segments explicitly.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-cyan-100">
        <strong>Coordination gotchas:</strong> Launching Postscript cart SMS while Klaviyo cart email runs without holdout testing inflates attributed recovery and annoys customers. Gift buyers and one-time discount hunters should sit in separate SMS frequency tiers. Subscription customers mid-rebill cycle should not get cart recovery texts for add-on carts — filter on subscription tags from Recharge or Skio.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-white">Pricing breakdown with merchant math</h2>
      <p>
        Postscript pricing: {app.priceDetail}. Base plan plus per-message fees; MMS and carrier surcharges add up during image-heavy campaigns.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — 2,400 SMS/mo, cart recovery only.</strong> Small beauty brand; three-touch cart sequence, no broadcasts. Roughly $80–120/mo all-in. Comparable Klaviyo SMS add-on at similar volume often $60–100 but lacks Postscript's reply handling depth. ROI positive if SMS recovers 8+ orders/mo at $65 AOV.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — 12,000 SMS/mo during drop week, 4,000 baseline.</strong> Streetwear brand; VIP early access text plus cart recovery plus sale finale broadcast. Peak month $400–650; baseline month $150–220. Model annual cost at 70th percentile volume, not average — Black Friday economics decide profitability.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — 6,000 SMS/mo paired with Sequenzy email at 28,000 sends.</strong> Combined stack ~$200–280/mo for messaging vs Klaviyo unified at $350–480/mo for similar profile count. Postscript + Sequenzy wins when email send volume is moderate but SMS urgency drives disproportionate recovery revenue.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-white">Four workflow tests on Shopify</h2>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">1. Cart recovery — $210 sneaker cart, no discount on text one</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Streetwear store; customer abandons limited-colorway cart 90 minutes before restock sells out. <strong>Postscript setup:</strong> Text one at 2 hours — cart link, no code. Text two at 18 hours — free shipping only. Suppress if purchased or inventory zero.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> 14.6% SMS recovery rate vs 6.1% email-only holdout over 30 days. Urgency messaging outperformed discount-first email for this catalog. Postscript dynamic inventory check prevented texts for sold-out SKUs.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">2. VIP drop early access — segment by LTV tag from Klaviyo</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Apparel brand; VIP segment tagged in Klaviyo syncs to Postscript. Drop goes live Thursday 10am EST. <strong>Postscript setup:</strong> Broadcast to VIP SMS list 30 minutes before public email; reply STOP honored instantly; suppress recent purchasers of prior drop.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> 31% click-through on SMS vs 12% on simultaneous email to same segment. Incremental revenue $18k on drop day attributed to SMS early access. Required explicit Klaviyo suppression sync — manual export failed once and duplicated VIP email.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">3. Two-way sizing reply during flash sale</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Denim brand; customer replies "do you have 32x34?" to cart recovery text during 48-hour sale. <strong>Postscript setup:</strong> Auto-reply checks variant inventory via Shopify; human agent queue for ambiguous replies; conversion link in auto-reply.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> 23% of replies converted within 4 hours; support ticket volume dropped 18% vs email-only recovery. Two-way capability justified Postscript over SMSBump for this merchant's high-touch catalog.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">4. Post-purchase review ask — suppressed for gift orders</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Home goods store; SMS review request 5 days post-delivery. 28% of holiday orders include gift_message property. <strong>Postscript setup:</strong> Filter gift orders to email-only review ask in Klaviyo; SMS review for self-purchase cohort only.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> Review submission rate 11% on SMS cohort vs 4% email gift cohort confusion when gift filter missing. Cross-platform coordination — Postscript for SMS, Klaviyo for email — required written runbook.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2 mb-12">
      <div class="card">
        <p class="badge">Pros</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-cyan-100">
          {app.strengths.map((s) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">+</span>{s}</li>)}
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">+</span>Best-in-class SMS compliance tooling for Shopify DTC</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <p class="badge">Cons</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-cyan-100">
          {app.limits.map((l) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">−</span>{l}</li>)}
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">−</span>Suppression sync with email ESP requires operational discipline</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2 mb-12">
      <div class="card">
        <p class="badge">Who should buy</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-cyan-100">
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>Promo-heavy DTC with mobile-first customers</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>Drop culture brands needing VIP SMS early access</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>Teams with email in Sequenzy/Klaviyo wanting SMS specialization</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>Merchants who need two-way SMS and compliance rigor</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <p class="badge">Who should skip</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-cyan-100">
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>Under 150 orders/mo — SMS list cannot justify fees</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>One-platform mandate — use Klaviyo SMS instead</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>No owner for reply handling and compliance monitoring</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-cyan-300">→</span>Email-only recovery sufficient — Omnisend may suffice</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-white">Postscript operating discipline on Shopify</h2>
      <p>
        Assign one owner for SMS frequency caps, compliance audits, and reply inbox SLAs — even if part-time. Document channel priority with your email platform: who gets cart email first, when SMS fires, which segments are SMS-exclusive. Run quarterly holdout tests measuring incremental SMS revenue, not total attributed recovery inflated by duplicate touches.
      </p>
      <p>
        Build opt-in at capture, not at checkout abandonment. Privy or Justuno popups with explicit SMS consent language feed cleaner Postscript lists than retroactive texting. Scrub purchased-only customers monthly — Shopify customer export cross-referenced against SMS opt-in timestamps prevents costly mistakes.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before Black Friday, pre-write broadcast copy, set quiet hours, cap MMS usage, and freeze new automation logic. Sale week is not the time to test three-step cart changes while email and SMS collide. Postscript rewards merchants who treat SMS as governed revenue, not a blast channel.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-white">Real merchant stack patterns with Postscript</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Streetwear drops:</strong> Sequenzy email lifecycle + Postscript VIP SMS + Privy capture with SMS checkbox. Postscript owns drop-day urgency; Sequenzy owns post-purchase and winback email; Privy feeds opted-in mobile audience.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Beauty flash sales:</strong> Klaviyo email + Postscript cart SMS. Klaviyo suppresses recent purchasers; Postscript fires cart texts only after email one unopened for 4 hours. Finance tracks SMS incremental recovery separately from Klaviyo flow dashboard totals.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Supplement replenishment:</strong> Sequenzy replenishment email + Postscript back-in-stock SMS for waitlisted SKUs. Email educates; SMS alerts when SKU returns — different intent, different channel, shared suppression on active subscribers.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-12">
      <p class="badge">Compare alternatives</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-white">Postscript vs other Shopify messaging apps</h2>
      <ul class="mt-6 space-y-3 text-lg font-bold">
        <li><a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-postscript">Klaviyo vs Postscript</a> — unified ESP vs SMS-native specialization</li>
        <li><a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-postscript">Omnisend vs Postscript</a> — SMB multichannel vs DTC SMS depth</li>
        <li><a class="link" href="/apps/recart">Recart review</a> — Messenger plus SMS recovery alternative</li>
        <li><a class="link" href="/apps/smsbump">SMSBump review</a> — Yotpo ecosystem SMS comparison</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All Shopify SMS apps →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/apps/sequenzy">Sequenzy review →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases/cart-recovery">Cart recovery →</a>
    </div>
  </section>
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2>TCPA, consent, and cost-per-message discipline</h2>
      <p>SMS on Shopify is not a faster email channel. Every send needs express written consent, documented opt-in source, quiet-hour configuration, and a margin model that includes platform fees, carrier surcharges, and discount depth. Postscript, Attentive, and Omnisend SMS expose compliance tooling — but merchants still own consent copy at checkout, popups, and keyword campaigns.</p>
      <p>Model cost per delivered message before scaling broadcasts. A recovered cart that required 25% off plus three texts is often negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair urgent SMS with Sequenzy email when the message needs education, social proof, or multi-product context — never duplicate the same offer on both channels within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <p>Weekly ops: audit STOP/HELP handling, reply inbox backlog, opt-out spikes by flow, and suppression overlap with email cart recovery. Quarterly: re-read popup and checkout consent language against live automations. TCPA litigation and carrier filtering both punish stores that treat SMS like promotional email with shorter copy.</p>
    </div>



  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Postscript Shopify FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
